WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.260
I'm going to be talking about the RStudio Pro Launcher and how this can change or help

00:00:13.260 --> 00:00:19.440
change where we run R stuff.

00:00:19.440 --> 00:00:21.400
So what is the Launcher?

00:00:21.400 --> 00:00:25.280
The Launcher will allow applications, in this case we're talking about RStudio Server Pro,

00:00:25.280 --> 00:00:29.840
to easily launch jobs, and in this case we're talking about R jobs, somewhere.

00:00:29.840 --> 00:00:33.759
Now this sounds pretty simple, but it opens up some interesting use cases.

00:00:33.759 --> 00:00:37.959
I'd like to show you some of the cool things it allows you to do.

00:00:37.959 --> 00:00:41.400
So I thought I'd start off with an example of how I've used the Launcher, then we can

00:00:41.400 --> 00:00:44.520
dive more into the details of how it actually works.

00:00:44.520 --> 00:00:49.080
So at the last RStudio conference, I saw Gyor's talk on five packages in five weeks, you might

00:00:49.080 --> 00:00:50.680
have been there.

00:00:50.680 --> 00:00:55.080
In it he mentions a post about creating portraits with text using R, so here's a portrait of

00:00:55.080 --> 00:00:59.160
Hadley made entirely of dplyr code.

00:00:59.200 --> 00:01:01.799
I read through his post and I thought it was interesting.

00:01:01.799 --> 00:01:04.519
So before this conference I thought it would be cool to create the same kind of portraits

00:01:04.519 --> 00:01:08.239
with all the RStudio employees and conference speakers using what Twitter profiles I had

00:01:08.239 --> 00:01:10.559
access to.

00:01:10.559 --> 00:01:12.120
So I get working on my script.

00:01:12.120 --> 00:01:15.919
I'm doing this work on RStudio Server Pro, connecting using a browser.

00:01:15.919 --> 00:01:20.760
It doesn't take that long because I have all the pieces, I just need to put it together.

00:01:20.760 --> 00:01:22.760
It does take some time to run, though.

00:01:22.760 --> 00:01:26.720
It downloads all the text and images, it does some transformation to it, and then it plots

00:01:26.720 --> 00:01:30.160
the text to create the image, and it does this one at a time.

00:01:30.160 --> 00:01:35.680
So I wait for it to finish, and then I have my beautiful Twitter artwork.

00:01:35.680 --> 00:01:40.480
So each one of these images is created using the text from the author's tweets.

00:01:40.480 --> 00:01:41.480
That's pretty cool, I guess.

00:01:41.480 --> 00:01:45.599
I didn't think it would be cool to do the same thing with the top 100 Twitter users

00:01:45.599 --> 00:01:49.440
by number of followers, and I don't want to wait as long, so I figure out how to parallelize

00:01:49.440 --> 00:01:50.440
my code.

00:01:50.440 --> 00:01:55.360
I only have access to a couple of CPU cores on this server, so it helps cut the time it

00:01:55.360 --> 00:02:00.879
would take in half.

00:02:00.879 --> 00:02:04.480
So it takes about seven minutes to complete with 100 images in those two cores, and basically

00:02:04.480 --> 00:02:09.199
I'm ignoring all of Joe's talk this morning on making things more efficient, and I'm just

00:02:09.199 --> 00:02:13.520
throwing money at it.

00:02:13.520 --> 00:02:17.199
So at this point, my imagination starts to go a little crazy to see what I could do next.

00:02:17.199 --> 00:02:20.759
So I'm a gamer, and I thought it'd be cool to take a video of the first level of Doom,

00:02:20.759 --> 00:02:25.179
separate all the individual frames, and then recreate each frame with this same portrait

00:02:25.179 --> 00:02:30.259
style using text from the source code of the game.

00:02:30.259 --> 00:02:36.339
So it seems like a good use of my time, right?

00:02:36.339 --> 00:02:38.619
Now that was a lot of individual frames to deal with.

00:02:38.619 --> 00:02:43.699
It was about 1,000 images, and it could take six, seven hours to complete, even if I parallelized

00:02:43.699 --> 00:02:48.419
my code, and I'm restricted on the server for the amount of CPU and memory, and it would

00:02:48.419 --> 00:02:54.660
be cost inefficient for me to have some really beefy system doing something like this.

00:02:54.660 --> 00:02:59.500
But I do have access to a Kubernetes cluster up on Google Cloud, and this cluster is actually

00:02:59.500 --> 00:03:02.300
set up for me to have a lot more CPU and memory.

00:03:02.300 --> 00:03:04.139
If you don't know what Kubernetes is, don't worry about it.

00:03:04.139 --> 00:03:05.660
We'll talk a little more about it later.

00:03:05.660 --> 00:03:09.979
And each one of these nodes has 32 CPUs, 120 gigabytes of memory, and I have access to

00:03:09.979 --> 00:03:13.059
use it on demand for some reason.

00:03:13.059 --> 00:03:17.059
Because of its auto-scaling ability, I could send the cluster this type of job, it'll scale

00:03:17.059 --> 00:03:23.539
up, and then when it's not in use, it'll scale back down, thus making it way cheaper to operate.

00:03:23.539 --> 00:03:30.899
So if only I could just use 25 cores or so, and I can get this done really fast.

00:03:30.899 --> 00:03:35.179
So there's ways that I can do that, but they can be somewhat painful, but nothing is fully

00:03:35.179 --> 00:03:39.839
integrated within the IDE until now.

00:03:39.839 --> 00:03:44.339
So this is introducing the RStudio launcher.

00:03:44.339 --> 00:03:48.699
So I'm on a server that has a launcher already configured and set up, and I have the ability

00:03:48.699 --> 00:03:52.899
to launch these jobs on the Kubernetes cluster right from RStudio.

00:03:52.899 --> 00:03:58.380
All I have to do is go to the new jobs pane in RStudio, which is new for the RStudio 1.2

00:03:58.380 --> 00:04:03.660
release, start a launcher job, select my script and whatever options I want, don't worry too

00:04:03.660 --> 00:04:09.639
much about the details here, in this case I'll choose 25 cores and I'll start it.

00:04:09.639 --> 00:04:14.020
The script will run in the cluster and I can see the status and output in the jobs pane.

00:04:14.020 --> 00:04:20.119
This will be running completely independent of my currently running R session.

00:04:20.119 --> 00:04:23.880
Now I'm able to do a much more intensive task in a much shorter amount of time.

00:04:23.880 --> 00:04:28.119
What would have taken forever now takes about 15 minutes with the 25 cores.

00:04:28.119 --> 00:04:32.239
It doesn't really look like you can see it very well, but it's pretty cool.

00:04:32.239 --> 00:04:35.679
This might seem like a silly example, but the ability to launch R jobs on a Kubernetes

00:04:35.679 --> 00:04:38.519
cluster opens up some neat possibilities.

00:04:38.519 --> 00:04:42.079
You can see how if you have an intensive job, you can utilize another processing environment

00:04:42.079 --> 00:04:45.720
to speed up that analysis.

00:04:45.720 --> 00:04:49.839
Now that you've seen one of the things a launcher can do, let's talk about what is actually

00:04:49.839 --> 00:04:50.839
going on.

00:04:50.839 --> 00:04:54.399
We've added in two additional layers into the system.

00:04:54.399 --> 00:04:58.079
The RStudio launcher is a separate service that is independent of RStudio server and

00:04:58.079 --> 00:05:06.519
it communicates with a plug-in to connect to these different environments.

00:05:06.519 --> 00:05:09.679
So what am I talking about with these plug-ins?

00:05:09.679 --> 00:05:14.279
So the core of the job launcher is simply a framework for loading external plug-ins

00:05:14.279 --> 00:05:19.519
which contain the actual logic for communicating with the job's destination.

00:05:19.519 --> 00:05:21.720
So how do these things work together?

00:05:21.720 --> 00:05:25.920
Once your plug-in is configured and the RStudio launcher process starts, it executes your

00:05:25.920 --> 00:05:34.160
plug-in process as a trial of itself and communicates with it via standard in and standard out.

00:05:34.160 --> 00:05:36.880
So what kind of plug-ins are available?

00:05:36.880 --> 00:05:43.399
So for the 1.2 release of RStudio, we are releasing three plug-ins, local, Kubernetes,

00:05:43.399 --> 00:05:45.040
and Slurm.

00:05:45.040 --> 00:05:47.959
And side note on Slurm plug-in, it's still in development and it's not really ready to

00:05:47.959 --> 00:05:52.559
be played with yet but it's going to be coming soon.

00:05:52.559 --> 00:05:54.600
So what about other plug-ins?

00:05:54.600 --> 00:05:57.679
We're still trying to figure out what comes next but we're planning on adding more plug-ins

00:05:57.679 --> 00:06:00.920
in later RStudio releases.

00:06:00.920 --> 00:06:06.480
But what if you have a super awesome processing platform that you use in your own company?

00:06:06.480 --> 00:06:10.440
Well good news is that you can create your own plug-ins.

00:06:10.440 --> 00:06:12.559
And here's the documentation to do so.

00:06:12.559 --> 00:06:15.079
And that should have everything you need to get up and running with whatever environment

00:06:15.079 --> 00:06:18.320
you want to connect to.

00:06:18.320 --> 00:06:20.359
So there are two types of jobs you can launch from RStudio.

00:06:20.359 --> 00:06:24.839
The first is ad hoc jobs and that's what we were talking about in the first example.

00:06:24.839 --> 00:06:29.200
You can use the jobs pane in the IDE to launch specific scripts to run wherever the plug-in

00:06:29.200 --> 00:06:31.440
is configured for.

00:06:31.440 --> 00:06:34.200
You might see that I snuck a Python job up there.

00:06:34.200 --> 00:06:40.000
The job launcher can also run Python jobs directly from RStudio.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:42.559
The second is containerized sessions.

00:06:42.559 --> 00:06:47.640
So in this example I developed my code with an R session on the RStudio server that lived

00:06:47.640 --> 00:06:49.399
on that box.

00:06:49.399 --> 00:06:52.679
This is where I wrote and tested my script and it's a session that's tied to the console

00:06:52.679 --> 00:06:54.640
in the IDE.

00:06:54.640 --> 00:06:59.239
Then I launched the script as an ad hoc job to the Kubernetes cluster.

00:06:59.239 --> 00:07:06.160
But with the launcher I can also develop and test directly on the cluster with a containerized

00:07:06.160 --> 00:07:07.160
session.

00:07:07.160 --> 00:07:11.399
I can write and debug the code interactively with all the capabilities your code will have

00:07:11.399 --> 00:07:12.739
when it runs.

00:07:12.739 --> 00:07:16.600
That means you can completely separate these R sessions from the RStudio server if you

00:07:16.600 --> 00:07:17.600
would like.

00:07:17.600 --> 00:07:22.720
And this is integrated within the RStudio UI.

00:07:22.720 --> 00:07:25.440
So typically you have a single server and everyone is forced to use the same version

00:07:25.440 --> 00:07:29.320
or versions of R and Linux dependencies and an admin has to maintain that box for those

00:07:29.320 --> 00:07:33.200
users if they need updates or new software.

00:07:33.200 --> 00:07:36.760
But with the launcher and containerized session those dependencies don't even have to be installed

00:07:36.760 --> 00:07:37.799
on the server.

00:07:37.799 --> 00:07:39.760
They live in the Docker image itself.

00:07:39.760 --> 00:07:44.160
So various users can be using different images with different versions of R, specific R packages

00:07:44.160 --> 00:07:46.440
installed by default.

00:07:46.440 --> 00:07:50.600
And this allows you to create those truly reproducible environments.

00:07:50.600 --> 00:07:58.160
Also these images can be shared and distributed on Docker Hub or any other container registry.

00:07:58.160 --> 00:08:01.679
So on the same RStudio server, user 1 can be running a session with a Docker image that

00:08:01.679 --> 00:08:07.799
contains a specific version of R, get specific Linux packages and user 2 could be running

00:08:07.799 --> 00:08:13.239
a completely different version of R and different R packages installed in shared libraries by

00:08:13.239 --> 00:08:15.040
default.

00:08:15.040 --> 00:08:18.239
Or one user could be running a bunch of different types of images for different sessions for

00:08:18.239 --> 00:08:21.000
various types of work.

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:24.679
And these dependencies are now self-contained and isolated from other containers being run

00:08:24.679 --> 00:08:31.200
so a user can completely screw up everything in the container and it won't affect the others.

00:08:31.200 --> 00:08:34.880
Because of this containerized session, one huge benefit is scaling.

00:08:34.880 --> 00:08:38.760
So currently with RStudio Server Pro, if you'd like to scale, you have to set up multiple

00:08:38.760 --> 00:08:41.880
RSP nodes with all the required dependencies and load balance between them.

00:08:41.880 --> 00:08:46.119
If you get more users and sessions, you have to provision more nodes and reconfigure the

00:08:46.119 --> 00:08:47.559
group.

00:08:47.559 --> 00:08:50.280
Things like autoscaling becomes a much harder problem to solve if that's what you want to

00:08:50.280 --> 00:08:51.280
do.

00:08:51.280 --> 00:08:55.960
But using the launcher, you can let a container orchestration platform handle that scaling

00:08:55.960 --> 00:08:56.960
for you.

00:08:56.960 --> 00:09:01.000
As you can see here, we have RSP running on one server with the launcher and the launcher

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:05.840
communicates with the Kubernetes cluster to create these containerized sessions there.

00:09:05.840 --> 00:09:10.880
Kubernetes has all that functionality to do the scaling for you.

00:09:10.880 --> 00:09:13.580
So this allows you to just have that one RSP server.

00:09:13.580 --> 00:09:18.280
You could have multiple for resiliency, but all the memory and processing load is kicked

00:09:18.280 --> 00:09:24.440
to the cluster and not on the RSP server itself.

00:09:24.440 --> 00:09:28.280
Now I'd like to demonstrate launching the two types of jobs from with RStudio Server.

00:09:28.280 --> 00:09:39.960
This includes ad hoc jobs and the containerized sessions.

00:09:39.960 --> 00:09:44.679
So here's RSP running the latest 1.2 release.

00:09:44.679 --> 00:09:49.679
New to 1.2 is this jobs pane, as some people have already talked about.

00:09:49.679 --> 00:09:54.479
And here I have a script that's just a test script that prints a message, it sleeps for

00:09:54.479 --> 00:09:57.559
a little bit and then prints the R version string.

00:09:57.559 --> 00:10:02.359
So in the jobs pane, I have the ability to start local jobs, but on RSP and if I have

00:10:02.359 --> 00:10:04.919
the launcher set up, I can also start launcher jobs.

00:10:04.919 --> 00:10:09.760
So first I'm going to start a local job with this test script, just to kind of show you

00:10:09.760 --> 00:10:13.320
what this jobs pane works or how it works.

00:10:13.320 --> 00:10:17.599
If you didn't see, Jonathan already talked about it.

00:10:17.599 --> 00:10:19.960
And so as you can see, I can watch the output as it comes in.

00:10:19.960 --> 00:10:26.000
It shows a progress bar and I can see a list of all my other running jobs.

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:32.520
And then while that's running, I have another script, and this is my top Twitter.rscript,

00:10:32.520 --> 00:10:39.200
which is the one I use to get the top 100 Twitter users, and I'm going to start this

00:10:39.200 --> 00:10:43.200
as a launcher job.

00:10:43.200 --> 00:10:47.880
So as you can see, I've got a little bit different options when I'm going to start a launcher

00:10:47.880 --> 00:10:48.880
job.

00:10:48.880 --> 00:10:52.280
I have the environment here that I can choose my R script or working directory, just like

00:10:52.280 --> 00:11:01.960
I can on local jobs, but then I can also name it, so I can name this RStudio.

00:11:01.960 --> 00:11:05.760
I can choose the cluster that I want this job, where this job to go to.

00:11:05.760 --> 00:11:11.719
Right now this RStudio server pro has the local plug-in and Kubernetes plug-in, and

00:11:11.719 --> 00:11:14.080
so I'm going to choose the Kubernetes plug-in.

00:11:14.080 --> 00:11:16.900
I can choose the amount of CPU and memory.

00:11:16.900 --> 00:11:21.119
You can see that it was defaulted to certain numbers, and I also have a maximum, and this

00:11:21.119 --> 00:11:27.599
can all be configured by an RStudio admin in the profiles.

00:11:27.599 --> 00:11:34.599
So for this script, I'm going to run with 10 CPUs, I'm going to leave it at 10 gigs,

00:11:34.599 --> 00:11:36.400
and then this is where I can choose my image.

00:11:36.400 --> 00:11:41.719
So I have a couple images already set up on Google Cloud Registry, and I also have the

00:11:41.719 --> 00:11:47.059
ability to choose other and choose whatever URL I want for whatever image I have.

00:11:47.059 --> 00:11:50.640
So you can choose a Docker Hub image or whatnot.

00:11:50.640 --> 00:11:54.239
So I'm going to go with this default that I have set up, that I have dependencies for

00:11:54.239 --> 00:12:00.280
the script, and I'm going to hit start.

00:12:00.280 --> 00:12:04.239
So as you can see, it's now running, it has this little icon showing that it's a launcher

00:12:04.239 --> 00:12:05.919
job instead of a local job.

00:12:05.919 --> 00:12:11.679
I can click into it to see the output, and then it will just continue to run.

00:12:11.679 --> 00:12:16.520
So I'm going to go back to this test script, and I'm going to change this so it doesn't

00:12:16.520 --> 00:12:20.440
take so long, and then I'm going to run this test script as a launcher job.

00:12:21.239 --> 00:12:26.000
So just to show off that you're running in a different environment, this current environment

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:30.679
that I'm in is running R version 3.5.1, and then I'm going to start this launcher job

00:12:30.679 --> 00:12:32.799
in a different image.

00:12:32.799 --> 00:12:40.679
So this one obviously doesn't need very much compute power.

00:12:40.679 --> 00:12:43.200
And I'm going to run in a different image.

00:12:43.200 --> 00:12:47.440
So some of you might be familiar with the Docker Hub image R base, and that will be

00:12:47.440 --> 00:12:51.359
running the latest version of R, which is R 3.5.2.

00:12:51.359 --> 00:12:59.080
So I'll see what the output is here.

00:12:59.080 --> 00:13:00.080
Start the job.

00:13:00.080 --> 00:13:03.320
Look at the output.

00:13:03.320 --> 00:13:07.640
And as you can see, in my current running environment, I'm running 3.5.1, and this image

00:13:07.640 --> 00:13:08.640
is 3.5.2.

00:13:08.640 --> 00:13:14.400
So you can see how you can run different images with whatever dependencies you have for whatever

00:13:14.400 --> 00:13:19.400
scripts you want to run.

00:13:19.400 --> 00:13:22.039
So now I want to show off containerized sessions.

00:13:22.039 --> 00:13:26.960
So Tarif showed off this a little bit in the keynote.

00:13:26.960 --> 00:13:30.159
But if you go to the RStudio Server Pro homepage, if you're not familiar with this, it shows

00:13:30.159 --> 00:13:35.159
your currently active sessions, you're currently running jobs, your completed jobs, and I'm

00:13:35.159 --> 00:13:41.440
going to go here to new to create a new session, and from here, I have the same type of options

00:13:41.440 --> 00:13:43.039
as I had before.

00:13:43.039 --> 00:13:44.039
So I'm going to name this.

00:13:44.039 --> 00:13:49.479
I'm going to choose the same cluster.

00:13:49.479 --> 00:14:06.320
I'm going to use the default two CPUs, 10 gigs of memory, and the same default image.

00:14:06.320 --> 00:14:13.000
So now this currently running RSP session is running in Kubernetes and not on the RSP

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:14.000
box.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:18.599
So it looks exactly the same, runs exactly the same, but now any CPU and memory you use

00:14:18.599 --> 00:14:30.039
is actually on that cluster.

00:14:30.039 --> 00:14:32.359
So I have a couple frequently asked questions here.

00:14:32.359 --> 00:14:33.359
Let's see.

00:14:33.359 --> 00:14:35.719
How do I get the launcher and plugins?

00:14:35.719 --> 00:14:40.119
So for the 1.2 release, the launcher will come bundled with RStudio Server Pro and include

00:14:40.119 --> 00:14:42.159
those three plugins that we talked about.

00:14:42.159 --> 00:14:47.880
The release is available as a preview currently if you want to download it and try it out.

00:14:47.880 --> 00:14:50.239
So will this come to the RStudio desktop?

00:14:50.239 --> 00:14:52.239
And the answer is yes, it will.

00:14:52.239 --> 00:14:53.919
But for the 1.3 release.

00:14:53.919 --> 00:15:00.200
So we're going to implement the launcher after this release and then we'll start working

00:15:00.200 --> 00:15:01.200
on 1.3.

00:15:02.200 --> 00:15:06.640
If you're unfamiliar with what RStudio Desktop Pro is, because it's only going to be for

00:15:06.640 --> 00:15:10.559
the Pro edition, it's an enhanced version of the IDE with enterprise feature that we're

00:15:10.559 --> 00:15:14.679
shipping with the 1.2 release.

00:15:14.679 --> 00:15:16.960
What about other RStudio products?

00:15:16.960 --> 00:15:20.679
So the launcher is something we eventually want our products to standardize on and so

00:15:20.679 --> 00:15:27.880
RStudio Connect and Package Manager will be integrating with the launcher in future releases.

00:15:27.880 --> 00:15:32.840
So to sum everything up, RStudio Job Launcher is a separate service bundled with RStudio

00:15:32.840 --> 00:15:34.719
Server Pro.

00:15:34.719 --> 00:15:38.760
It's available now as a preview release.

00:15:38.760 --> 00:15:41.640
The three plugins are Kubernetes, Slurm, and Local.

00:15:41.640 --> 00:15:46.000
And you can do some cool stuff with it, like launch ad hoc jobs so you can run those computationally

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:50.000
expensive R Python scripts somewhere else.

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:53.919
You can run these containerized sessions, so you can run an isolated environment with

00:15:53.919 --> 00:16:00.039
all the desired dependencies, create reproducible environments, and this will help you scale.

00:16:00.039 --> 00:16:01.559
So it should make admins happy.

00:16:01.559 --> 00:16:05.440
So I have some further reading here.

00:16:05.440 --> 00:16:10.820
Here is the documentation for our admin guide of RStudio Server Pro and then also the Job

00:16:10.820 --> 00:16:12.919
Launcher documentation.

00:16:12.919 --> 00:16:16.080
And if you have any additional questions you want to talk to us, please meet us up in the

00:16:16.080 --> 00:16:17.919
professional lounge.

00:16:17.919 --> 00:16:18.919
Thank you very much.

00:16:19.239 --> 00:16:20.280
Thank you.

00:16:27.799 --> 00:16:32.400
So we actually have time for a couple of questions, if anyone has some.

00:16:32.400 --> 00:16:36.059
